30|$|The 75  % {{atmospheric}} humidity {{was obtained by}} letting a small flow (~ 1  dm 3 /h) of pure CO 2 gas or N 2 gas pass through water, saturated with NaCl, into the chamber containing the samples. After exposure the samples were measured with <b>diffuse</b> <b>reflection</b> Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy using a Nicolet Magna-IR 560 with an insert cell for <b>diffuse</b> <b>reflection</b> spectroscopy. The measurement range lies between 400 and 4, 000  cm− 1 with a nominal resolution of 2  cm− 1.|$|R
40|$|A {{method for}} {{determining}} bandgap energy using <b>diffuse</b> <b>reflection</b> is presented. The method uses bifurcated fiber optic cables {{to measure the}} <b>diffuse</b> <b>reflection</b> of diffusely reflective materials. The absorption spectrum is extrapolated from the <b>diffuse</b> <b>reflection</b> spectrum and {{used to determine the}} bandgap of powdered materials. The theory of nonspecular reflection, the Kubelka-Munk model, and bandgap structure is explored. The methods, procedure, and equipment involved in measurements are detailed. The bandgap energies of titanium dioxide, tin sulfide, and 10 percent tin doped indium oxide are determined. The measured bandgap energy of TiO₂ agrees within 0. 03 eV of the accepted value. The measured bandgap energy of SnS was inconsistent with the accepted value and is most likely attributable to incorrect infrared spectral data. The measured bandgap energy of In₂₋[subscript]xSn[subscript]xO₃ agrees within 0. 1 eV of the accepted value...|$|R
